{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608695/1958012801/0907.xml":{"full_text":"WFATHCR FORECAST\nMostly sunny today. Cloudy tonight, lowest\nnear 33. Cloudy, little temperature change\ntomorrow. <Full report, Page A-2.)\nTemperatures Today\nMidnight 39 6 a.m... 37 II am.... 39\n3 am.-- 38 8 am... 37 Noon 40\n4am 37 10 am... 38 I pm.... 41\n106th Year. No. 28.\nU. S. Projects\nBuoy District\nBusiness Hope\nTrade Board Parley\nForesees Continued\nPopulation Growth\nBy FRANCIS r. DOUGLAS\n\u2022t\u00bbr attff Writer\nWashington businessmen took\ntook today at the area's ex\npanding economy and saw new\nbuildings worth many millions\nof dollars, city highways cost\ning more than a half billion,\nans other developments needed\nby a community of two mil\nlion.\nAnd the population Is still\ngrowing. A forecast put it at\n30 per cent more by mid-IMS\nand M per cent above the 1960\nfigure, or 3.3 million, in 1980.\nThe look at the bustling\nactivities was provided at the\nannual Business Outlook Con\nference of the Washington\nBoard of Trade. Co-operating\nin the scrutiny of the present\nand the future at the Willard\nHotel were the Advertising and\nSales Executive Clubs of Wash\nington and the American Mar\nketing Association.\nHighlights of Fie tare\nAmong the highlights of the\npicture were these:\nThe Government has under\nway preliminary work on four\nFederal office buildings to cost\napproximately SIOO million,\nplus construction of the $36\nmillion Smithsonian Museum\nof History and Technology,\nwhich is expected to be started\nlater this year. These are in\naddition to the Central Intelli\ngence Agency and State Depart\nment buildings on which work\nis now under wax.\nA six-fold increase is expected\nin the assessed value of the\nSouthwest redevelopment areas\nwhen construction is completed\nSo fsr, purchases in Areas B\nand C by the Redevelopment\nLand Agency have channeled\n$35 million into the Investment\nmarket.\nThe total cost of completing\nthe various Federal highway\nprojects in Washington through\n1971 will ran to nearly $550\nmillion.\nWashington's second biggest\nindustry\u2014conventions and\ntourists\u2014brings to S3OO million\na year.\nFashes Aaditsrieas Flaw\nAn overall picture of the\narea's problems and progress\nwas given by John W. Thomp\nson. jr. He is chairman of the\nBoard of Trade's Co-ordinat\ning Committee on the Future\nof Washington and president\nof The Evening Btar Broad\ncasting Ho\nCharles E. Phillips, president\nof the Equitable Life Insurance\nCo. of Washington, delivered\nMr. Thompson\u2019s paper. Mr.\nThompson was prevented (torn\ndoing so by laryngitis.\nHe called for the revival of\nthe auditorium commission\nheaded by Mr*. Eugene Meyer. I\nWhile the Board of Trade, he\nexplained, opposed the Foggy\nBottom site recommended by\nthat commission, the type and\nscope of the auditorium it pro\nposed is far more satisfactory\nthan a project of restricted use\nproposed to be built on the\nMall.\nIn contrast to the generally\nbright picture was the predic\ntion by another speaker who\n\u2022ought to answer the question\nwhether the proopsed zoning\nregulations would restrict\ngrowth. The answer was no.\nfor the area as a whole. But if\nthe zoning recommendations\nnow considered are adopted, it\nwas predicted there would be\nlower land values and hence\nsmaller tax collections, and\nbusinesses and apartment\nhouses would go beyond the\ncity\u2019s limits\nIn Mr. Thompsons general\nContinued on Fage A-5. Cel. I\n\nCzechs Aiding Ceylon\nVIENNA. Jan. 28 \u2014In-\ndustrial Czechoslovakia. Mos\ncow's chief satellite instru\nment for economic penetration\nof the Middle East and Asia,\nannounced today another Asian\ncontract\u2014delivery of a sugar\nrefinery for Ceylon.\nStar Want Ad\nSells House\nFirst Day\n*ff.'\nRecently, Mr. B. T. wanted\nto sell his house. He plsced\nan ad In the producUve\ncolumns of Star Classified\nand found a buyer the first\nday his ad ran.\nIf you want to sell your\nhouse get fast action\nby always using Star Class\nified Washington's\npreferred classified medium\nby more than 3 to 1 accord\ning to an American Re\nsearch Bureau survey.\nColl STerling 3-5000\nAik tor an ad-taker\nI\n\u00a9he finning Skf\nV_ V J V V WITH SUNDAY MORNING EDITION\nPhone ST. 3-5000\nRoy Campanella's Neck\nFractured in Auto Crash\nBULLETIN\nOLEN COVE. N. Y.. Jan.\n38 (A I ).\u2014Doctors performed a\nfour-hour 30-minute opera\ntion today on Roy Cam pe\nncils for a fractutred neck,\nbut did not immediately make\npublic a report on it Com\npendia came out of the op\nerating room about 1 pm.\nOLEN COVE. N. Y.. Jan. 38\n(A*).\u2014Catcher Roy Cam pencils\nof. the Los Angeles Dodgers\nsuffered a fractured neck early\ntoday when his car skidded on\na slippery street, overturned\nand crashed into a pole.\nHit condition was termed\ncritical and a lengthy operation\nwas begun.\nCampanella. conscious but\nparalysed from a pinched\nnerve in his spinal cord, dis\ncussed the situation calmly\nwith doctors. Told an imme\ndiate operation was believed\nneeded, he replied:\n\u201cWhatever you fellows think\nis necessary.\"\nThe operation was described\nas a laminectomy, a procedure\nto relieve pressure from the\nfracture on the spinal cord. A\nspokesman at Community Hos\npital here said this was neces\nssury before it could be deter\nmined whether any permanent\ninjury had been sustained. No\nother injury waa apparent im\nmediately.\nThe operation waa begun by\na team of seven surgeons at\n8:30 am. The surgery had been\nMilitary Position Sound,\nMcElroy Tells Senators\nBy U\u00bb \u00bb\u2014rHI\u00abS rrw I\nSecretary of Defense McElroy\ntold Senators today that \"on\nthe whole our military position i\nis sound.'' At the same time i\nhe urged speedy appropriation\nof more than 81 billion to step i\nup programs for ballistic mis\nsiles and related defenses.\nMr. McElroy was leadoff wlt\nnew in a closed-door session of\nthe Senate Appropriations\nCommittee on an emergency\nmoney bill containing *1.280,-\n000.000 of new funds plus trans\nfer authority on 8150 million of\nold funds.\nflnl i.nr.r.nr.\ninn AppfArAnfr\nTije measure won unanimous\npassage in the House last\nThursday and is expected to i\nget similar Senate treatment.'\npossibly with some additions\nIt waa Mr. McElroy's initial\nHouse Group\nWill Study\nKeating Plan\nThe House Judiciary Com\nmittee today ordered a staff\nstudy of Representative Keat\nings' proposal for an overall\nstudy of Federal laws Involving\nthe Insanity defense.\nMr Keating. Republican of\nNew York, ranking Republican\nD. C CitixtM Are Net Getting Pro\ntection on the Streets Pege l-l\non the committee, outlined his\nproposal at a closed meeting of\nthe committee today. The com\nmittee decided to defer action\non Mr. Keating's proposal\npending the outcome of a stall\nstudy.\nChairman Celler said after\nthe meeting that the question\n\"was of lively interest to every\nbody'' but that many procedu\nral questions were involved in\nmaking the proposed investiga\ntion\n\"We want to know where we\nare going and whether this\nproblem should be one for a\nlegislative group to undertake.\u201d\nhe explained. \u201cOoing into this\nis like setting sail on an un\ncharted course. We want to\nchart our course.\"\nAmong the questions involved,\nhe said, was whether any legis\nlation to come out of the study\nwould involve the District of\nColumbia statutes or general\nones. Mr. Keating has empha\nsized that the series of deci\nsions involving claims of insan\nity in the courts here are symp\ntomatic of widespread confu\nsion about insanity laws.\n3.3 Million Population\nForecast for Area by 'BO\nThe District area'* population, estimated at 2.005D00\non January 1, is forecast to reach 2,133.000 by 1960, to total\n2,410,000 by 1965 and to be 3.3 million by 1910. These esti\nmates and forecast are by Dr. Jerome P. Pickard, research\ndirector of the Washington Board of Trade.\nEstimate. Forecast Inc.\nJanuary April July April \u2018SB\n1.1858. 1.1960. 1.1965. 1.1980 80\nWashington. D. C. 865,000 870.000 890.000 940.000 9\nMontgomery Co.. Md. 317.000 355.000 435.000 870.000 111\nPr. Oeorges Co. Md. 336.000 375.000 460.000 770.000 139\nMaryland Suburban 653.000 730.000 895.000 1.440.000 130\nArlington Co.. Va.... 169.000 180.000 190.000 310.000 24\nAlexandria. Va. 90,000 95.000 105400 125.000 38\nFalls Church. Va. 10.200 14.000 12.000 15,000 47\nFairfax Co.. Va 218.000 347.000 318.000 670.000 161\nVirginia Suburban 487,000 533.000 625.000 920J80 88\nMetropolitan Area 2.005.000 2.133,000 2.410,600 3.300.000 64\nIn addition. Prince William County, Va., with an eatl\nhnatod 1980 population of 200\u00a300, will be included in that\nMetropolitan Area In 1980. F\nWASHINGTON, D. C. f TUESDAY, JANUARY 28, PAGES\n'l3\nROY CAMPANELLA\nCondition Critical\nexpected to last about two\nhours but several hours later\nthere was no report from the\noperating room.\nCampanella's automobile ac\ncident occurred at 3:30 am. on\na Olen Cove street not far from\nhis home. He was pinned to\nthe wreckage for half an hour\nbefore emergency workers could\nfree him.\nThe word was immediately\nrelayed to Dodger officials to\nLot Angeles, where the club was\nrecently moved from Brooklyn.\nBuxzy Bavasi, club vice presi\ndent. voiced great concern over\ni See CAMPANELLA. Page A-34\nappearance before the Senate\npurse string committee as Sec\nretary of Defense. He took over\nthe post from Charles E. Wil\nson. auto industry executive,\nafter the end of the last session\nof Congress.\nMr. McElroy said the emer\ngency fund measure \"is in ef\nfect. an advance action of the\n1859 program\u201d already under\nconsideration by the House.\nThat was a reference to the\ndefense money Mil for the fiscal\nyear that begins next July 1.\nMr McElroy's prepared testi\nmony was made available to\nnewsmen outside the closed\ndOOr M3JIQT\nAccompanying him were As\nsistant Secretary of Defense\n1 McNeil, sometimes called the\nfinancial manater of the Pen\ntagon. and Oen. Nathan P.\nTwining, chairman of the Joint\nChiefs of Staff\nAccepts Increase\nMr. McElroy readily accepted\nan increase of S4O million dol\nlars made by the House above\nthe transfer authority initially\nasked by the President and\nDefense Department\nOs this amount. S2O million\nis for research and develop\nment on the Army's Pershing\nmissile, planned as a solid-fuel\nsuccessor to the liquid-fuel\nRedstone.\nThe decision to push this\nwas reached after the budget\nrequest went to Congress. Mr.\nMcElroy said.\nThe other extra 820 million,\nhe said, would be used to \u201cpro\nvide accelerated support for\nsecond generation\u2019 divisional\nand corps-type missiles for the\nArmy the La Crosse. Little\nJohn \u2014and related electronic\nequipment.\"\nThe Secretary also spelled\nout some details on the new\ntop-level Advanced Research\ni Projects Agency he set up in\nthe Defense Department.\nResearch Role\n\"Initially, the new agency\nwill be given full responsibility\nfor research and development\nof the anti-missile missile and\nfor outer space projects.\" Mr.\nMcElroy said.\n\"Other projects of this kind\nwhich are not clearly the re\nsponsibillty of a single military\ndepartment or which may be\nmore appropriately performed\nby this agency may also be as\nsigned tq the agency.\"\nMr. McElroy asked the Sen\nate to approve creation of 25\nnew top-pay places for scien\ntists and technicians who will\nwork for ARPA. The House ap\nproved this.\nThe Secretary disclosed that\nSee DEFENSE. Fage A-5\nBaghdad Group\nPlans Facilities\nCosting Billions\nReported Moving\nToward Unified\nDefense Command\nANKARA. Turkey. Jan. 38\n(A I ).\u2014The Baghdad Pact coun\ncil of ministers today approved\nlong-term plans for a strategic\nsystem of roads, ports, airfields\nand radio telecommunications.\nIf carried out. the project win\ncoet billions of dollars over a\nperiod of several years.\nThe live-nation conference\u2014\nwith Secretary of State John\nFoster Dulles sitting as an\nAmerican observer\u2014okayed the\nplan in approving the report of\nthe pact's Military Committee.\nOther aspects of the commit\ntee's report were not immedi\nately disclosed.\nInformed sources said the\ncouncil waa moving, however,\ntoward turning the military\nplanning group into a full\nblown unified command. An\nIranian move last year to set\nup a NATO-type command\nfailed to go through because\nof proposals that Iran's King.\nShah Mohammed Reaa Pah\nlevi. become the supreme com\nmander.\nWidespread FaeiUUes\nThe plans approved today\nwould provide a rommunica\ntlons hookup from the Dar\ndanelles to Khyber Pass, trunk\nand lateral highways, civil air\nports which could be used for\nmilitary purposes and seaports\nwith harbor and storage fa\ncilities on the Mediterranean.\nPersian Oulf and Indian Ocean.\nThe conference continued a\nsurvey of the Middle East po\nlitical scene.\nConference sources reported!\nthere was no unanimous sup-'\nport for Iraq's demand that\nthe council define Its policy to\nward a Palestine settlement.\nPremier Nurt Said of Iraq\nyesterday pressed the council to\nsupport Arab demands that\nIsrael be forced back to the\nfrontiers suggested by the\nUnited Nations to 1947.\nSecret Military Report 4\nThe secret parts of the Mili\ntary Committee's report were\nbelieved to hove recommended:\n1. That any major assault\nfrom the north must be met as\nfar as possible in the craggy\nmountain pastes between Rus\nsia and Turkey. Iraq and Iran.\n2. National forces of the\nregional Moslem members, who\nalso include Pakistan, must be\ndeveloped and modernized al\nthough not necessarily with\nnuclear weapons.\n3. The United States and\nBritain, the other two partici\npating nations, will speed sup*\nply of conventional arms which\nmay become surplus to needs of\ntheir own forces\u2014including\nwarships, fighter planes, radar\nwarning equipment, antiair\ncraft missiles and tanks.\nAgreed on Broad Strategy\nThe military planners al\nready have agreed on the broad\nstrategic lines of Middle East\nern defense now that the\nUnited Btates has assumed a\nfirm commitment to Join in\nrepulsing any attack from the\nnorth.\nAs understood here Baghdad\nPact defense strategy now\nhinges firmly on American\n\"mobile power\" in the form of\naircraft operating from the 6th\nFleet in the Mediterranean,\nand from land bases in Turkey.\nSaudi Arabia. Libya and\nj Morocco. Their capacity to\ncarry H-bombs into the south\ncentral region of Russia\u2014\nl where there are.many industrial\nand military targets\u2014would\nundoubtedly be supported by\nBritish air power based In\nCyprus, Iraq and Aden.\nEisenhower\nGoing to Rites\nOs Brother\nPresident Elsenhower will\ntake off for Kansas City in\nthe Columbine 111 tomorrow\nmorning to attend the funeral\nof his oldest brother Arthur.\n71. who died of a heart attack\nSaturday night.\nThe presidential plane will\nleave at 8:15 a.m. The funeral\nwill be held at 1 p.m. at a\nKansas City funeral home.\nWith the President will be\nhis younger brother. Dr. Milton\nElsenhower, president of Johns\nHopkins University; his per\nsonal physician. MaJ. Gen. How\nard McC. Snyder; his military\naide. Col. Robert L. Schuls. and\nPress Secretary James C.\nHagerty.\nThe President and Dr. Eisen\nhower will be joined in Kansas\nCity by a third brother. Earl,\nof La Orange, 111. Edgar Ei\nsenhower of Tacoma. Wash., is\nnot expected to be able to at\ntend.\nThere will be services later\nin New York and burial will be\nthere. These arrangements have\nnot been completed.\nThe President and his party\nplan to fly back to Washing\nton immediately after the serv\nices, arriving here about 8:40\nPresident Will Press\nPlans for Defense Shift\n\u25a0fiSfip 1 ,'Mjl\nm W 1 M I\nHjk \u2022*f\u00ae\nmlkr\nW\n\nAT ANTITRUST HEARING\u2014Senator Kefauver (left) chats with Walter\nReuther, president of the United Auto Workers Union, as the Senate\nAntitrust and Monopoly Subcommittee opens hearings. Mr. Kefauver\nis chairman of the subcommittee.\u2014AP wirephoto.\nBig Jupiter-C\nPoised on Pad\nj j\nArmy Gets Chance\nTo Try Satellite\nCARS CANAVERAL. F1a.. 1\nJan. 38 (<PV\u2014A mighty Jupiter-\nC missile stood poised on its\nlaunching pad here today, i\nready for its effort to propel\na 30-pound American earth\nsatelltte tnto space. The blast\noff is expected tomorrow or\nThursday.\nThis Is a chance the Army\nhas long awaited It claims it\ncould have fired a satellite into\norbit as far back as 1955. ldng\n1 before the Russian Sputniks, if\nIt had not been ordered to\nstand aside and let the Navy\ndo the Job wtth its Vanguard\nrocket.\nNow. in the wake of the\ni Navy\u2019s latest failure to get the\ntemperamental Vanguard off\nthe ground, there is furious ac\ntivity around the Jupiter-C fir\ning platform. Obviously, the\nArmy has its go-ahead and is\nclose to its zero hour.\nThe weather is perfect. The\ntall Jupiter tower stands in\nbright sunshine and. workmen\nswarming over It can be seen\nclearly from the beaches out\nside the top-secret firing range.\nWay Cleared far Jupiter\nNobody talks officially, but\noptimism Is high.\nMany experts have expressed\nthe opinion that the Jupiter-C.\na creation of the Oerman sci\nentist. Wernher von Braun, has\na better chance than the Van\nl guard to put the first American\n''moon\u201d into orbit around the\nearth.\nThe first Vanguard blew up\non its firing pad here December\nA after an immense publicity\nbuildup. Last week, a four-dky\neffort to shoot a second Van\nguard ended in failure. Bad\nSee JUPITER, Page A-5|\n5 Days of Rain and Snow\nBring Northeast Floods\nBOSTON. Jan. 28 (ft).\u2014 A'\nflood crisis along the Charles\nt River grew today as rain and\nI light snow pelted New England\nfor the fifth straight day.\nThe Charles surpassed the\nflood stage two days ago and\ni was expected to crest 3 feet\ni above flood level by tomorrow,\nSeveral bridges spanning the\nriver have been closed and\nr numerous streets in Great Bos-\nI ton communities along the\nriver were under several inches\nof water today.\nWhile Greater Boston got\ni mostly rain, other sections of\nNew England were blanketed\nwith snow last night and early\ni today.\nThe heavy rains caused a\nsection of s Boston 6c Maine\nroadbed to give way at Somer\nvllle and was blamed for de\nrallment of six cars of a 119-\ncar freight train. No one was\ninjured, but some delays in\ncommuter servloe resulted.\nThomas J. Donnelly, Massa\ni ahusetts Civil Defense director.\nJJpWed the situation along the\nReuther Gills Car Firms\nBig Factor in Recession\nTells Senators 'Big Three' Keep\nPrices at 'Unreasonable Levels'\nBy WILLIAM HINES\nI Otar staff Wrlttr\nUnited Automobile Workers President Walter P. Reuther\nsaid today the big three automobile corporations are \"short\nchanging\u201d the national economy by keeping the price of\nautomobiles at unreasonably high levels.\nTestifying before a Senate Judiciary Subcommittee on\nantitrust and monopoly. Mr. Reuther put the bulk of the\nblame for the general down\nturn in business on the .big\nthree\u2014General Motors. Ford\nand Chrysler.\n\"At the present level of\nprices,\" Mr. Reuther said, \"the\nindustry has priced out of the\nmarket several million Amer\nicans who would otherwise be\nbuying cars.\"\nThe loss of these sales. Mr.\nReuther said, inhibited the pro\nduction not only of automobiles,\nbut also of steel, rubber, glass,\ntextiles and other things that\ngo into the making of cars.\nO'Mahnnry Sponsors Bill\nThe auto union chief made\nhis charges at the openifig of\nan investigation into a bill,\noriginally sponsored 10 years\nago by Senator O'Mahoney,\nDemocrat of Wyoming, to regu\nlate pricing in industries where\npower is concentrated.\nSenator Kefauver. Democrat\nof Tennessee and chairman of\nthe subcommittee, set the stage\nfor Mr. Reuther's testimony in\nan opening statement in which\nhe said: \"Increased concentra\ntion in our basic industries is\nmaking it more difficult for\nnew enterprises to be energised\nin America.\"\nSenator Kefauver produced a\nchart showing the percentage\nof the automobile market con\ntrolled by the Big Three. Aver\naging 88 per cent over a 10-year\nperiod, this level has risen\nsteadily from 81 per cent in'\n1 Charles yesterday and reported\ni to Gov. Foster Purcolo that\nwhile the waters were breach\nlng the banks in some places,\nno grave danger exists.\nThousands of cellars were\n1 flooded and sewers clogged In\nsome communities, posing a\nhealth problem.\nThe Neponaet River crested\nlate yesterday at 10.77 feet and\nI last night was reported reced\ning slowly.\nYesterday's rain sent the\ni total rainfall for January to\n8.56 inches, breaking the Jan\nuary record of 7.60 Inches set\nin January, 1875.\nNorwood and Canton Alr\nports were closed because of\nthe accumulation of water on\ni the fields.\nThe greatest damage was re\nported In Eastern Massachu\nsetts, but other communities in\nNew England also were af\ni fected.\nAbout 150 families in York\nBench, Me., were without cen\ntral heat as streets flooded two\nto giree feet. Merchants used\ni on Main street.\nHome Delivered: 11%\n1949 to 98 per cent in 1956. the\nchart showed.\nOther Witnesses\nSenator Kefauver said Mr.\nReuther's testimony will be the\nlead-off in a series of presen\ntations from both sides of the\nbargaining table. General Mo\ntors President Harlow Curtice\nwill testify Thursday Ford\nVice President T. O. Yntema\nnext Tuesday: Chrysler Presi\ndent L. L. Colbert on February\n6. and George Romney, presi\ndent of American Motors Corp..\non February 7.\nMr. Reuther's testimony was\nbolstered by a 110-page presen\ntation and 29 tables and charts\nand supported by UAW Econo\nmist Nat Weinberg.\nRepeatedly. Mr. Reuther cited\nfigures which he said indicated\ndisproportionate profits en\njoyed by the big three at the\nexoense of the total \u2022economy.\nStating that 115.000 manu\nfacturing corporations in the\nUnited States had made $24 6\nbillion before taxes in 1956. Mr.\nReuther said the big three got\n$2.3 billion of this.\nOn net worth, he said. Gen\neral Motors was averaging 27.4\nper cent profits annually after\ntaxes over the last 10 years.\nFord averaging 15.9 per\ncent and Chrysler, 17.8 per cent.\nPreftts vs. Wages\nThe UAW chief declared that\nwhile Oeneral Motors profits\nhave gone up 270 per cent be\ntween 1947 and 1956, wages of\nproduction workers in that\ncorporation had gone up only\n72 per cent. The comparable\nfigures for Ford, he added, were\n1 329 per cent increase in profits\nand 70 per cent increase in\nwages.\nAsked by Senator Wiley. Re\npublican of Wisconsin, whether\ni he did not favor further con\ni centratlon of power in the big\nthree, Mr. Reuther said;\n1 \"No, I would think it would\n1 be a constructive thing for the\nAmerican economy if we had\nmore competition in the auto\nindustry.\u201d\n1 The trouble with the econ\nomy now, Mr. Reuther said.\nSee PRICES. Page A-8\n81/LLE77N\nRed Offer Rejected\nThe State Department to\nday rejected Nikita Khru\nshchev's suggestion that\nEast-West leaders seek to\nsettle easy problems first at\na' summit conference and\nI then tackle tougher Issues, j\n\\.arller Story on Page A-5)\nMetropolitan\nEdition\nNew York Markets Page A-21\nMay Offer\nHis Project\nIn Sequence\nBy GARNETT D. HORNER\nStar Staff Writer\nPresident Eisenhower may\ntry to apeed up action on re\norganizing the Defense De\npartment by tending a series\nof recommendations to Con\ngrew rather than waiting to\nget them all into one package.\nThis was indicated by Senate\nRepublican Leader Knowland\ntoday after he and other\nG. O. P. congressional leaders\nconferred with the President\nat the White House.\nSenator Knowland and House\nRepublican Leader Martin told\nnewsmen the conferees agreed\nthat some legislation by Con\ngress would be necessary to\ncarry out needed reorganiza\ntion of the military establish\nment to achieve greater unity\nin direction of the armed force*.\nThe President is giving the\nreorganization problem hia\npersonal attention. Senator\nKnowland said. He added:\n\"There is going to be no\nunnecessary delay. I atn cure\nit will be moved along as\nrapidly as the President be\nlieves it can be done.\u201d\nSeries of Moves Forecast\nThe Senator said he thinks\nit is \"entirely possible\" that\nthe President may send Con\ngress a series of separate rec\nommendations. He'said there\nmight be agreement within the\nadministration on some top\npriority move which would be\nrecommended to Congress be\nfore working out all details on\nother matters that could be\nsubmitted later.\nBome phases of the upcom\ning Pentagon reorganization\nmay be done by executive\norder. Senator Knowland told\nQuestioners. But. be said, the\nPresident feels that all th*\nthings needed cannot be ac\ncomplished without new legis\nlation.\nSenator Knowland said he\nthinks the President has a\n\u201ctentative\" decision on some of\nthe things he wants to do to\nimprove efficiency of the mili\ntary establishment but still if\nexploring other ideas. He re\nfused to Indicate what specific\nmoves the President may have\nin mind.\nWhile he expects defense re\norganization recommendations\nto be sent to Congress \u201cearly\nin this session.\u201d Senator Know\nland refused to specify any\ndate. Defense Secretary Me-\nElroy has said he is aiming at\nthe end of March for submis-'\nsion of his recommendations to\nthe President.\nPostal Rate Boost Discussed\nBesides defense reorganisa\ntion. Senator Knowland said\nthe conferees discussed admin\nistration moves for a postal rata\nincrease.\nPostmaster General Summer\nfield reiterated to the O. O. F.\ncongressional leaders, the Sen\nator reported, the importance\nof getting rate increase legisla\ntion through Congress \u201creason\nably early\" in this session.\nThe administration is asking\na raise to 5 cents postage for\nout-of-town letters and 4 cents\nfor local letters, along with\nrate increases for other classes\nof mall, so as to cut down the\npostal deficit.\nSenator Knowland said the\nRepublican leaders felt it would\nbe \u201cwiser\" to have the rate in\ncrease bill passed before Con\ngress approves pay raises for\npostal workers. He said he r\nthinks there is a \"reasonably\ngood chance\" to pass the rate\nlegislation this session.\nHARDY HIKERS\nIGNORE WEATHER\nSUB FREEZING WEATHER\ndoesn't discourage Washington I'M\nhikers To leers about these hardy\nwinter walkers, see George Huber t\nstory in The Star's Leisure Sports\nman Section, Rage A-25.\nHOW \"DEER\" are your property\nrights? For a discussion of the lana\nowner s rights when a tunnel it\nheaded hit way, tee Phil Yeager and\nfahn Stork's article on Rage A-15,\nA THUMRING DELEGATION\nfrom Jeannette, Ra, turned out\nyesterday to honor John H. Dent,\nfirst as their townsmen to tit is Con\ngress. For an account of tha avast,\ntee Isabelle Shelton's story in tha\nWomen's Section, Rage 8-4.\nGuide for Readers\nAmute\u2019tt A 11-19 Leisure Sp'tt A 25\nBusiness and Lott, Found A 3\nFin'ca A-20-21 Music l-|\nClassified I 1-14 Obituary A-16\nComics 1-17-19 Sports A-22-2S\nEditorial A-14 TV-Rodio 816\nEdit'l Articles A-15 Woman's\nFeature Rage 8-15 1 Section 8-4 7\nHov* Tha Slot Delivered to\nYour Horn* Doily and Sunday\nSTerlmq 3-SOOO\n5 CENTS","height":"28800","width":"18619"}}
